WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.070 --> 00:00:02.470
If you watch the news during
a presidential election,

00:00:02.470 --> 00:00:03.939
you’ll hear a lot of this:

00:00:03.939 --> 00:00:06.000
“What do the national polls look like?”

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:07.215
“Hillary Clinton’s national lead…”

00:00:07.215 --> 00:00:08.929
“Nationally, Joe Biden is currently ahead.”

00:00:08.929 --> 00:00:12.980
But these national polls don’t
actually tell you who’s going to win.

00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:17.199
“Throw the national polls out the window,
they don’t matter at all.

00:00:17.199 --> 00:00:19.000
What matters are those swing states.”

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.696
Ah yes. The swing states.

00:00:21.696 --> 00:00:25.449
Most democracies around the world
elect their head of state with a popular vote:

00:00:25.449 --> 00:00:28.270
So, whoever gets the most votes wins.

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:31.369
But in America we do it a little differently.

00:00:31.369 --> 00:00:33.870
The US is the only country
that picks its president

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:37.047
using something called the Electoral College.

00:00:37.047 --> 00:00:39.640
It’s made up of delegates from each US state.

00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:42.776
When Americans vote for president,
what they’re actually voting for,

00:00:42.776 --> 00:00:45.050
is who their state will vote for.

00:00:45.050 --> 00:00:48.251
This is why, every so often,
someone wins the presidency

00:00:48.251 --> 00:00:50.538
without winning the popular vote.

00:00:50.538 --> 00:00:54.554
That’s happened twice
in just the past 20 years.

00:00:54.554 --> 00:00:59.590
The majority of Americans do not like this
system, and haven’t for a long time.

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:02.620
Both political parties have made attempts
to get rid of it.

00:01:02.620 --> 00:01:06.555
So why does the US
still use the Electoral College?

00:01:06.555 --> 00:01:11.044
And who actually benefits from it?

00:01:12.270 --> 00:01:16.340
The Electoral College is based on
how people are represented in Congress:

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:20.496
where each state has a number of
representatives based on its population,

00:01:20.496 --> 00:01:23.590
and every state also gets two senators.

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:27.670
So, for example, let’s look at Texas, which
has a huge population,

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:30.000
and Vermont, which has a really small one.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.043
Texas has 36 representatives in Congress.
Vermont only gets one.

00:01:35.043 --> 00:01:37.324
Representatives in both states
each represent

00:01:37.324 --> 00:01:39.690
roughly the same number of people.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:42.560
In the Electoral College, a state gets the
same number of delegates

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:46.630
as their Congressional representatives, plus
two — for each senator.

00:01:46.630 --> 00:01:51.119
So Texas has 38 electoral votes.
Vermont has 3.

00:01:51.119 --> 00:01:54.901
But this combination makes the number
of people each delegate represents

00:01:54.901 --> 00:01:57.148
way different between states:

00:01:57.148 --> 00:02:01.615
In Texas, one electoral delegate represents
three times the amount of people

00:02:01.615 --> 00:02:03.659
as one in Vermont.

00:02:03.659 --> 00:02:09.310
And that makes each individual person’s
vote in Vermont a lot more influential.

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:13.589
The Electoral College creates
discrepancies like this all over the country.

00:02:13.589 --> 00:02:19.190
A voter in Wyoming is worth three and a half
times as much as a voter in California.

00:02:19.190 --> 00:02:23.673
The winner of the presidential election is
the candidate who gets 270 or more

00:02:23.673 --> 00:02:27.000
of these Electoral College votes.

00:02:27.427 --> 00:02:31.348
These are the results of the 2016 election,
by state.

00:02:31.348 --> 00:02:36.750
You’re probably more familiar with this version
of it: a map of red states, and blue states.

00:02:36.750 --> 00:02:43.330
But this chart tells a different story. You can
see that no state is actually all-red or all-blue.

00:02:43.330 --> 00:02:47.280
But almost every state awards its electoral
votes the same way:

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:51.780
The candidate who gets the most votes
in a state, gets ALL its electoral votes.

00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:57.000
If they win the state by 1%, they win 100%
of the electoral votes.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.230
In 2016, more than 4 million people
voted for Donald Trump in California.

00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:07.250
In fact, more people voted for him there
than in any other state except for two.

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:10.160
But it didn’t matter. Hillary Clinton got
more votes there,

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:13.706
so she got all 55 of its electoral votes.

00:03:13.706 --> 00:03:18.590
Clinton never even campaigned in California.
Polling showed she’d easily win the state.

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:23.861
Trump only visited Texas once; he knew he
basically had that state’s electoral votes locked.

00:03:23.861 --> 00:03:28.329
But they both visited Florida,
35 or more times.

00:03:28.329 --> 00:03:31.440
That’s because Florida
is usually a “swing state”:

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:36.090
Polls show that the vote there could swing
to one party or another in nearly every election.

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:42.620
Trump only won it in 2016 by 100,000 votes,
out of more than 9 million.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:47.487
Swing states have changed over time, thanks
to shifting demographics and political views.

00:03:47.487 --> 00:03:49.890
And it’s states like these
where presidential candidates

00:03:49.890 --> 00:03:52.780
spend most of their time campaigning.

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:58.680
It also means these states have way more
influence over the election than these ones.

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:04.622
A study found that voters in Michigan had 51 times
the amount of influence on the 2016 election

00:04:04.622 --> 00:04:07.182
as someone from a state like Utah.

00:04:07.182 --> 00:04:12.360
Voters in states like California, or Missouri,
mattered very little.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.070
Swing states are where the election actually
takes place.

00:04:15.070 --> 00:04:17.166
They get the attention and the influence.

00:04:17.166 --> 00:04:20.510
And they only exist
because of the Electoral College.

00:04:20.510 --> 00:04:22.730
It doesn’t seem very fair.

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:25.260
But the Electoral College
has always shifted power

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:27.780
away from some people
and towards others.

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:30.770
It’s how it was designed.

00:04:30.770 --> 00:04:32.980
Back when there were
just a few states, not 50,

00:04:32.980 --> 00:04:36.980
they had to get all the states to agree on
the Constitution.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:40.650
One problem: The Northern states, which were
largely anti-slavery,

00:04:40.650 --> 00:04:44.970
wanted only free people to count in the population towards electoral votes.

00:04:44.970 --> 00:04:46.810
Which they had more of.

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:51.540
The pro-slavery Southern states were worried
that they would be constantly outvoted,

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:55.590
and wanted enslaved people to count
in determining the population.

00:04:55.590 --> 00:04:59.870
As a compromise, they settled on
something called the “three-fifths clause.“

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:05.780
It established that an enslaved person
would only count as 3/5 of a person.

00:05:05.780 --> 00:05:10.190
In 1800, Pennsylvania, a northern state,
and Virginia, a southern one,

00:05:10.190 --> 00:05:12.960
had about the same number
of free people living there.

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:17.263
But Virginia was also home to hundreds
of thousands of enslaved people,

00:05:17.263 --> 00:05:19.752
who had no freedom,
let alone a vote,

00:05:19.752 --> 00:05:24.167
and ended up with more votes
in the Electoral College than Pennsylvania.

00:05:24.167 --> 00:05:31.530
That year, those extra electoral votes gave
the candidate from Virginia just enough to win.

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:33.900
Even after the US finally abolished slavery,

00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:36.770
and eventually gave Black Americans
the right to vote,

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:39.840
White Southern leaders found ways to keep
them from voting,

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:45.670
like with discriminating laws like poll taxes,
and acts of violence.

00:05:45.670 --> 00:05:49.340
This meant they continued to have
overrepresentation in the Electoral College

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:53.390
on behalf of a large population
that couldn’t vote.

00:05:53.390 --> 00:05:58.063
The first time Congress attempted to replace
the Electoral College with a simple popular vote

00:05:58.063 --> 00:06:00.425
was back in 1816.

00:06:00.425 --> 00:06:02.720
But senators from Southern states blocked it,

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:05.650
saying it would be “deeply injurious”
to them.

00:06:05.650 --> 00:06:09.181
In 1969, Congress came even closer:

00:06:09.181 --> 00:06:12.639
replacing the Electoral College had support
in both parties,

00:06:12.639 --> 00:06:14.530
and even passed the House.

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:17.320
But it was blocked again by Southern senators.

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:19.130
A senator from Alabama wrote,

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:23.350
“The Electoral College is one of the South’s
few remaining political safeguards.

00:06:23.350 --> 00:06:24.630
Let’s keep it.”

00:06:24.630 --> 00:06:30.303
Why change a system that historically had,
and still was benefiting White Southerners?

00:06:30.303 --> 00:06:33.910
Today, the states that the Electoral College
benefits have changed,

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:37.240
but it’s still making some voters
more powerful than others.

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:41.750
If we look at the states with a lot of electoral
votes, for not a lot of people,

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:45.130
and the states with a little electoral votes,
for a lot of people,

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:49.570
these states are a lot whiter
and less diverse than the rest of America.

00:06:49.570 --> 00:06:53.032
And many of these states
are Republican strongholds.

00:06:53.032 --> 00:06:55.490
These tend to vote Democratic.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:58.789
That’s one reason the two most recent Republican presidents

00:06:58.789 --> 00:07:02.712
have won the Electoral College
without winning the popular vote.

00:07:02.712 --> 00:07:07.616
And since it’s currently Democrats that are
primarily disadvantaged by the Electoral College,

00:07:07.616 --> 00:07:10.840
they’re the ones leading the charge
to replace it with a popular vote.

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:16.460
“Get rid of the Electoral College, and every
vote counts.”

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:21.530
But as politics have changed, the people most
critical of the Electoral College have, too.

00:07:21.530 --> 00:07:26.390
In the 1948 presidential election,
New York ended up being the major swing state.

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:31.200
A Congressman from Texas said, “I have no
objection to the Negro in Harlem voting.

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:35.210
But I do resent the fact that his vote is worth
a hundred times as much...

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:38.292
as the vote of a white man in Texas.”

00:07:38.292 --> 00:07:39.849
Swing states change.

00:07:39.849 --> 00:07:45.964
What doesn’t, is that the Electoral College gives
certain people more power to pick the president.

00:07:45.964 --> 00:07:51.914
And its biggest defenders have always
been those who benefit the most from it.

